Like, guys, please. If there’s an issue where a lot of people are harassing someone, just *call out the harassment* without bringing the ship into it, even if it’s the same ship. Don’t throw the rest of the fandom under the bus for something that just muddies your point anyway

I will also say this focus on x ship being racist based on some peoples’ bad behavior also puts PoC who like that ship in an absolutely awful position. From one side we’re called on to Defend The Ship From Accusations Of Racism, to the other we’re traitors to be harassed.

And then when there is an issue with someone actually being racist, the callouts use the exact same terms as the “clone/clone ships are inherently racist” instead of focusing on actual things they’ve done, and everyone doesn’t think anything of it because they’ve heard it before.

This is a *big* issues in SW Prequels fandom. People sometimes handle clone/clone ships racially —> “clone/clone shippers are racist” —> people trying to just enjoy their clone/clone with an adopted daughter fluff get harassed for being racist.

Couching these issues in the same terms as ship wars is profoundly unhelpful. People *do* get harassed regularly for their ships, and the similarity of the discourse makes it to easy to mistake one for the other.

Because even ships themselves aren’t monoliths - there’s always multiple different ways you can handle any given ship. If someone is using racist tropes in a ship fic, that is not a reflection on the ship, it is a reflection on the *writer*.

If someone is harassing a PoC, what their ships are or aren’t isn’t the issue. The harassment is the issue. So we should *address the harassment*, and not opine about the racism of x shippers as if any fandom is a monolith and everyone who enjoys a given ship is the same.

Broadly speaking, I don’t find racism in fandom analysis that is strongly focused on what people are or aren’t shipping to be particularly compelling. What a person ships is a red herring to the real issue: how they’re behaving towards real life people.

@backthatelfup The huge monopoly The Zon has on selfpub frustrates me to no end, to the point where going wide is strongly advised against in all my groups because KU makes up such a huge market share it’s like throwing away money. And it SUCKS and I hope the needle moves

@backthatelfup I personally intend to thumb my nose at those norms - illustrated cover AND illustrated interior, because those norms will never change unless someone challenges them. But broadly speaking people in selfpub are not trying to make their books indistinguishable from tradpub

@backthatelfup Generally speaking the trad and selfpub readership are WILDLY different groups, and selfpub is extremely reliant on the preferences of K*ndle Unlimited users specifically, leading to a lot of sameness with things like covers

Not essential, but useful. It's a tool like any other, like any sort of research. But, as per my previous thread, I don't think there's an issue of people just categorically ignoring older works, because it's more useful to investigate along a theme rather than a period

I *don't* think authors are morally obligated to work with Heady Themes, but I do think that if you are it's useful to look at what other people have said about those themes, some of them from a previous artistic generation from you and your peers.

And I will say again: this is for CRAFT reading, as part of the research one does AS AN AUTHOR. If you're just a reader go forth and read whatever the fuck you want. Same if you're not working with any particular Themes and whatnot.

Even if it's not ~in dialogue with the masters~, a modern book can absolutely have something worth paying attention to from a craft standpoint. Ideas don't only have merit if they're part of a Lineage

I broadly am not super compelled by any argument that's highly dismissive of modern works as a default. As a default, I consider modern authors to be my peers and will extend respect to their work. Looking to what my peers are doing *is* also craft work
Crucially, it is important to BOTH be reading older works (to see what ground has been tread, so if you retread it it's on purpose), AND modern works (to see how your peers are handling the subject)

I would say rather than some nebulous "It is necessary to read The Classics," if your goal is craft reading then you should be reading a variety of works along a targeted theme or subject, from a variety of periods

And as a high end raider, I very much enjoy the way FF caters to casuals because I am busy/low energy and their systems make it easier for me to participate. Versus WoW which is basically another job if you want to raid, which is also the only Real Fun Thing they have

Like it boils down to me as “why isn’t this game catering to me/high end raiders” when I’m like “hell yeah!!!” whenever someone tells me about something they had fun with that I don’t care about (usually PvP)
Like it’s definitely fine if you don’t enjoy FF but it’s very disingenuous to act like the Literal Selling Points of the game for people are *flaws*

Like yeah WoW’s huge sprawling raids are super fucking cool but also I absolutely never had the time or the energy to go through one all in one go and I specifically play FF for it’s much more bite sized approach
Like anything I can think of would involve completely restructuring the gameplay loop or combat system and like at that point you should really just play another game if you hate it so much
Like what do we actually want to move to WoW’s gearing system???? Fuck off, no way. Adding the equivalent of EX/Savage to dungeons would be hella fun but I don’t think of that a *flaw*

“But most of the players are casuals so they don’t have motivation to fix these flaws” Fucking so? Raiding isn’t everything, and I like raiding. Plus the ways the devs actively avoid FOMO except for maybe very low effort seasonal events is GOOD

“There’s no skill trees, everyone who plays one class has the same rotation” Which is also true in WoW if you raid, but also like….. that allows the devs to balance the jobs really finely so that Absolutely Everything is viable at the highest levels of play
Like getting pots and food for raiding is SO much less of a pain than in WoW because the crafting/gathering system is really robust and people do it for fun, increasing supply. Win fucking win!

“Oh people always say it has so many different types of content as if I CARE about any of that” my dude that’s WHY that’s a positive, if you want to only do high end raiding you can do that but then people who DON’T want to do that also have fun things to do

If you’re consistently a dick to other people in your field, your *peers*, editors and agents are absolutely going to notice and likely not want to work with you because dicks are generally unpleasant to work with

Also, to any writers of such dark things trying to break into the tradpub scene: writing grimdark or otherwise dark fiction isn’t an excuse to be as much of a dick as you want. Tradpub involves a lot of collaboration, and you do still need soft skills.

Curation is inherent in any reader’s experience. So… curate? If you don’t like the popular books, don’t fucking read them! Find people who like the same sort of thing you like and hang out with them! And don’t be a fucking dick to people who like other things, this isn’t hard

Like, to be clear, I don’t exclusively read grimdark or dark fiction. I read very widely in the (adult) genre. I find the idea that, for instance, TV plots are *dominant* in adult SFF utterly laughable. But even if it was true, like, you physically can’t read every single book

Like some stuff is always going to be more popular than other stuff. If you group genres by popularity some are going to be higher than others. That’s not a judgement on their validity, in either direction, that’s just how lists work.

“But this other thing is more popular than grimdark!” Why should I give a shit? I can still easily find books to read I like. Like. Fuck off, other peoples’ tastes being different than you isn’t an attack.

Like even if you want to make an argument that it’s somehow ~the dominant form of SFF~ like…. You can just read and write non-dominant types of fiction. Grimdark still gets published. “Dominant” doesn’t mean “every single thing ever”

As someone who very much enjoys Dark Fiction/Grimdark, I really just Do Not See other people writing and enjoying more happy and hopeful things as some sort of problem. Like. Both can exist. The existence of hopepunk does not eliminate grimdark.

So while, again, I think “YA is getting worse” is absolute bullshit, I *do* wish we could expand our emotional ranges to something beyond Only Happy Endings. Also if you were reading this and going “well what about” PLEASE send it to me oh my god I love it and CANNOT FIND IT

I wanted the pain! I wanted the tragedy! I still do now, I just have the general emotional maturity to be chill when I can’t find it except to post disappointed memes in a Discord channel after my monthly failure to find romantic tragedy books

I do find it very very strange that a category of books that targets an age range of people who have a Notable Stereotype about being angsty has such, such a focus on HEAs. I’m uninterested in HEA romance plots now. I DESPISED them as a teenager

But it’s more than just romance-focused plots. It *also* follows the *genre* Romance conventions when it uses those plots - namely the HEA. Again, fine, if you can find alternatives, but it’s difficult to impossible. And that? That would’ve made me quit reading as a teenager.

Modern YA is veryyyyyyy focused on its romance plots, which would be fine if it were easy to find stuff that wasn’t, but uh, it’s not particularly, and I know from friends in the field that this is very much A Thing publishers are targeting and pushing for

I regularly get YA recommended to me because I am a queer BIPOC that likes fantasy, and I read really fast so they’re low commitment for me - for reference, I can get through a Brandon Sanderson in a day. I’ve bounced off of every single one I’ve tried to read.

While the “YA is getting worse” convo is absolutely laughable, I do think it’s worth talking about how like… as a teenager I didn’t like how many happy endings there were, and how much romanced focused it was, and this was 15-20 years ago.

This is why people refer to Romeo & Juliet as a romance! They are not making a genre statement, and they wouldn’t look for it in the Romance section. They’re asking themselves “what is it that I remember about this book, oh yeah, there’s a central romance” and communicating that

We’re just using a word that efficiently gets across what we want! To people outside of Category Romance, “romance” just means a strong romantic focus, usually if not the plot, then the primary element you remember about the plot. The PRIMARY element.

Like. Please. The people trying to use profoundly common words like “romance” to describe books that don’t necessarily fit into Category Romance are not trying to take away your books. I do not look for romantic tragedies in the Romance section. None of us are.

I am simultaneously exhausted by the assumption that the only way for a romantic relationship to exist in a book without a specific type of Happy Ending is a subplot. It has to be a book “with romantic elements” which can dramatically undersell the importance of the relationship

If you want your A Specific Type Of Happy Ending genre, sure! But PLEASE stop framing everything that don’t end on a Everything Is Now Sunshine note as Horrifying Tragedy. It’s dramatically more complicated than that, and “happy ending” doesn’t mean the same thing to everyone.

Or being told in the comments that we needed to “tone down our aggressiveness” despite not actually being more aggressive than the white girls we were debating against. Or me getting the aggressive comment despite my white partner genuinely being a really aggressive debater

*That* was how me and my brown debate partner could be seen as a Scary Team despite consistently losing. Our judges’ comments were full of effusive praise for “being articulate!” while also ranking us low in the scores that have to do with what you would think articulateness was

I remember just not being able to wrap my head around it. We would be excited if we won more than one debate in the tournament. My last year I ended up partnering with a white girl, and she told me my research materials were the most highly desired across the entire debate league

Like. Y’all. Union organizing and strikes aren’t just a matter of “Company Evil Hurt Company By Any Means Possible.” Bargaining has a strategy. It requires leverage and different situations call for different leverages. For example small local business are a lot easier to boycott
*vibrates in animal crossing*

“Company has regular amount of demand but runs out of product because of the strike and the stores downgrade their displays and regular customers just start buying other stuff” has more long term consequences for companies than a temporary dip in sales, and is WAY easier to do
